title: Australian teenager Minna Atherton breaks world record for 100m backstroke in 54.89 seconds
text:
An Australian teenager has broken the world record for the women's 100m backstroke.

Minna Atherton, 19, raced to victory in the International Swimming League in Budapest, Hungary in 54.89 seconds on Sunday night.

The time eclipses the previous record of 55.03 set by Hungarian Katinka Hosszú in Qatar in 2014.

Minna Atherton (pictured), 19, raced to victory in the International Swimming League in Budapest, Hungary in 54.89 seconds on Sunday night

Atherton, from Brisbane, couldn't contain her delight as she spoke to reporters after the win.

'It's amazing,' she said.

'I can't really believe it yet. That's pretty exciting, I'm super happy with that swim. I'm stoked!'

Atherton was representing her team London Roar during the event where she also won the 4x100m medley relay.

In that race, which was before her world record performance, she clocked a time of 55.12 for her 100m backstroke leg.

'The first time I went out with my team and obviously I was just a bit off,' Atherton said afterwards.

'But I came out for my second (run) and gave it a red-hot crack.'

The former Brisbane Girls Grammar School student, who came second in the 2019 world championships, now has her sights set on a gold medal at the Tokyo Olympics in 2020.
